on, England":"Compton, Devon, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1328–6 July 1380":"1328–6. července 1380","1328–1380":"1328–1380","1334–1380":"1334–1380","1380–1428":"1380–1428","1298–1349":"1298–1349","1184–Female":"1184–Zesnulá","1349":"1349","about 1370":"okolo 1370","1337":"1337","1334":"1334","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","6 July 1380":"6. července 1380","1184":"1184","1380":"1380","1428":"1428","1328":"1328","before 1328":"před 1328","Compton, Devonshire, England":"Compton, Devon, Anglie","England":"Anglie","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","Marldon, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Marldon, Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, Anglie","Marldon, Devon, England":"Marldon, Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","Compton, Devon, England":"Compton, Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1328–6 July 1380":"1328–6. juli 1380","1328–1380":"1328–1380","1334–1380":"1334–1380","1380–1428":"1380–1428","1298–1349":"1298–1349","1184–Female":"1184–Afdød","1349":"1349","about 1370":"omkring 1370","1337":"1337","1334":"1334","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","6 July 1380":"6. juli 1380","1184":"1184","1380":"1380","1428":"1428","1328":"1328","before 1328":"før 1328","Compton, Devonshire, England":"Compton, Devon, England","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Marldon, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Marldon, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Marldon, Devon, England":"Marldon, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Compton, Devon, England":"Compton, Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1328–6 July 1380":"1328–6 juli 1380","1328–1380":"1328–1380","1334–1380":"1334–1380","1380–1428":"1380–1428","1298–1349":"1298–1349","1184–Female":"1184–Overleden","1349":"1349","about 1370":"circa 1370","1337":"1337","1334":"1334","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","6 July 1380":"6 juli 1380","1184":"1184","1380":"1380","1428":"1428","1328":"1328","before 1328":"vóór 1328","Compton, Devonshire, England":"Compton, Devon, England","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Marldon, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Marldon, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Marldon, Devon, England":"Marldon, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Compton, Devon, England":"Compton, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1328–6 July 1380":"1328–6 July 1380","1328–1380":"1328–1380","1334–1380":"1334–1380","1380–1428":"1380–1428","1298–1349":"1298–1349","1184–Female":"1184–Deceased","1349":"1349","about 1370":"about 1370","1337":"1337","1334":"1334","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","6 July 1380":"6 July 1380","1184":"1184","1380":"1380","1428":"1428","1328":"1328","before 1328":"before 1328","Compton, Devonshire, England":"Compton, Devon, England","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Marldon, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Marldon, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Marldon, Devon, England":"Marldon, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Compton, Devon, England":"Compton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gilbert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), French, and German: from the personal name <i>Giselbert</i>, composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gīsil</i> ‘pledge, hostage, noble youth’ (see   Giesel  ) + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This personal name enjoyed considerable popularity in England during the Middle Ages, partly as a result of the fame of Saint Gilbert of Sempringham (1085–1189), the founder of the only native English monastic order.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","History: The Devon family of Gilbert can be traced to Geoffrey Gilbert (died 1349), who represented Totnes in Parliament in 1326. His descendants included Sir Humphrey Gilbert (died 1583), who discovered Newfoundland. — Étienne Gilbert from Aulnay in Vienne, France, married Marguerite Thibault in Neuville, QC, in 1683. Louis Gilbert <i>dit</i> Comtois from Besançon in Doubs married Anne Jacques in Charlesbourg, QC, in 1722. Pierre Gilbert from Barbezieux-Saint-Hilaire in Charente, France, married Marie-Angélique Dufour in Petite-Rivière-Saint-François, QC, in 1756. Charles Dupuis <i>dit</i> Gilbert from Rosnay in Indre, France, married Marie-Jeanne Brunet in Sainte-Foy, QC, in 1741."],"variants":[{"name":"Gieseke","meanings":["North German: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Giselbert</i> (see   Gilbert  ). Compare   Giesecke  ."]},{"name":"Giliberto","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Sal, Salvatore, Constantino, Costantino, Emilio, Rosario, Santo, Sebastiano, Vittorio.","Italian: from an ancient Germanic personal name (see   Gilbert  )."]},{"name":"Gipp","meanings":["English (East Anglia): from the personal name <i>Gipp</i>, a pet form of   Gilbert  . See also   Gibbs  . Alternatively, if pronounced with a soft <i>g</i>, it is a variant of <b>Jepp</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Jep(p)</i>, <i>Gep(pe)</i>, a pet form of   Jeffrey  .","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with the stem <i>geb</i> ‘gift’, as in <i>Gebhard</i> (see   Gebhardt  )."]},{"name":"Gilbertson","meanings":["English (northern): from the personal name   Gilbert   + <i>-son</i>."]},{"name":"Giesel","meanings":["German: from the personal name <i>Giesel</i>, a short form of any of several ancient Germanic personal names with the first element <i>gīsil</i> ‘pledge, hostage, noble offspring’. In ancient and medieval ancient Germanic society, the younger children of kings and princes were sometimes sent to be brought up at the court of a neighboring ruler, as a pledge of peace between the two nations or clans. Thus, the male personal name <i>Gisil</i> and its feminine equivalent <i>Gisela</i> mean both ‘pledge’ and ‘noble offspring’."]},{"name":"Gilb","meanings":["German: from a short form of the personal name   Gilbert  ."]},{"name":"Gibert","meanings":["French and German: from a shortened form of the personal name   Gilbert  . This name was also brought to England by Huguenot refugees in the 17th century.","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Giese","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Klaus, Erwin, Heiner, Heinz, Uwe, Aloysius, Armin, Dieter, Erhard, Ewald, Frieda.","German, Dutch, and Danish: from a short form of the personal name <i>Giselbert</i> (see   Gilbert  ), or any other ancient Germanic name with <i>gīsil</i> ‘hostage, pledge, noble offspring’ (see   Giesel  ) as the first element. Compare   Giesey  ."]},{"name":"Gibby","meanings":["English (Pembrokeshire): from a Middle English pet form of the personal name   Gilbert  ."]},{"name":"Gebbie","meanings":["Scottish (Ayrshire and Lanarkshire): from a pet form of the Norman personal name <i>Giselbert</i> (see   Gilbert  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":0,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":9,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Gilbert Sr was born in 1328, in Devon, England, his father, Sir Galfrid Geoffrey Gilbert II, was 30 and his mother, Joan Compton, was 144. He married Elizabeth de Champernowne about 1370, in Compton, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 6 July 1380, in Compton, Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 52, and was buried in Marldon, Devon, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1328–6 July 1380":"1328–6. juuli 1380","1328–1380":"1328–1380","1334–1380":"1334–1380","1380–1428":"1380–1428","1298–1349":"1298–1349","1184–Female":"1184–Surnud","1349":"1349","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1337":"1337","1334":"1334","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","6 July 1380":"6. juuli 1380","1184":"1184","1380":"1380","1428":"1428","1328":"1328","before 1328":"enne 1328","Compton, Devonshire, England":"Compton, Devon, England","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Marldon, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Marldon, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Marldon, Devon, England":"Marldon, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Compton, Devon, England":"Compton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1328–6 July 1380":"1328–6. heinäkuuta 1380","1328–1380":"1328–1380","1334–1380":"1334–1380","1380–1428":"1380–1428","1298–1349":"1298–1349","1